#Text=Tidal flats are banks of mud or sand that are exposed at low tide.
#Text=Greywackes are sandstones containing rock fragments and clay minerals.
#Text=Caldera is a large crater or depression resulting from a powerful volcanic explosion or the collapse of the central part of a volcano.
#Text=Catchment is an area that is drained by a river and defined by the surrounding watershed.
#Text=Chute is a narrow channel with a swift current, applied to rivers, the straits between the mainland and islands, and to furrows produced by avalanches on hill slopes.
#Text=Coquina is a carbonate rock which consists largely or wholly of mechanically sorted, weakly to moderately cemented fossil debris.
#Text=Corestone is a spheroidal boulder of relatively unweathered rock surrounded by saprolite and formed by sub-surface weathering of a joint block.
#Text=Corrasion is the mechanical erosion of rock surfaces by the impact of moving debris.
#Text=Corridor karst is a type of karst characterized by long, narrow chasms enlarged by the action of water and into which surface runoff or stream may flow.
#Text=Daya is a shallow depression found primarily in areas underlain by limestone bedrock or calcrete as a result of solution.
#Text=De Geer Moraine is a glacial landform consisting of swarms of small ridges oriented perpendicular to the ice flow direction.
#Text=Dreikanter is a shaped pebble found on the surface in desert regions and periglacial areas with three distinct facets on its upper surface as a result of wind abrasion.
#Text=Drift ice is any type of floating ice that has drifted from its point of origin and broken into pieces small enough for a ship to sail through.
#Text=Ferricrete is a type of duricrust consisting of an iron-pan or near-surface zone of iron sesquioxide cementation.
#Text=Fiard is a coastal inlet produced by the drowning of an undulating landscape of shallow valleys and low interfluves.
#Text=Foreshore is the part of a coast lying between the lowest low-water line and the average high-water mark.
